---
import Layout from '@/layouts/Layout.astro';

// The founder/origin page — press anchor, brand SEO, and (later) the blog's
// author home. Story raw material: growth_strategy.md Pillar 5; posture rules
// (coach not auditor, villain = value left on the table, "couldn't not
// wouldn't"): product_decisions.md → Brand voice & positioning.
export const prerender = true;
---
<Layout
  title="About — Lanyard"
  description="Lanyard is an independent iOS app for theme park annual passholders, built in Orlando by a passholder who found his own way into the world he loves."
>
  <article class="legal">
    <div class="legal__inner">
      <p class="kicker legal__label">Built by a passholder</p>
      <h1 class="display legal__title">Found another way in.</h1>

      <p class="legal__lead">Lanyard is an independent iOS app for theme park annual passholders: blockouts, perks, events, park hours, and payback in one place. It's made in Winter Garden, Florida, a short drive from the parks, by Dan Seals, a passholder who wanted more from his passes and built the tool to get it.</p>

      <figure class="about__photo">
        <img
          src="/assets/dan-winter-garden.webp"
          alt="Dan Seals smiling in downtown Winter Garden, Florida, brick storefronts behind him."
          width="1200" height="1200" loading="lazy" decoding="async"
        />
        <figcaption>Plant Street, Winter Garden, between park days.</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <h2>The story</h2>
      <p>Lanyard started with an admission. Dan loves the parks, and he wanted a way to be part of the world around them, the one the vloggers and bloggers and podcasters live in. The honest problem: <em>"I wish I could be a vlogger. I just don't think I could do that every day."</em></p>
      <p>So he built something instead. As his wife, Antonia, put it: <em>"You realized you weren't going to be someone who vlogs their experience, so you found your own way into that world."</em></p>
      <p>The thing he built is the tool he wanted as a passholder: one app that knows every pass he holds, which parks he can walk into today, which perks he's leaving on the table, what's on the calendar across all his parks, and the day each pass pays for itself.</p>

      <h2>What Lanyard believes</h2>
      <p>You should never have to wonder whether your pass is worth it. It will be. Lanyard makes sure of it.</p>
      <p>That's the whole posture. Lanyard never sits in judgment of a pass you already bought. The villain is value left on the table: the perk you forgot to claim, the blockout you drove into, the event you found out about a week late. Your park's app is there to sell you the next thing. Lanyard is there to make sure you got your money's worth from the thing you already bought.</p>
      <p>It's also the tool no single park <em>could</em> build. Most passholders in Central Florida hold more than one pass, and no operator can track its competitors' blockouts or redeem their perks. The one thing this tool has to be is neutral. That takes an independent app, built by someone whose only stake is the passholder's side of the math.</p>

      <h2>Independent, by design</h2>
      <p>Lanyard is not affiliated with, endorsed by, or sponsored by any park operator. Park names appear in the app because they're facts about your passes, nothing more. And what you track in Lanyard stays yours: no account, no sign-up, never linked to your identity, never sold.</p>
      <p>There's a reason the privacy posture runs deep: security is Dan's day job. He's a chief information security officer by profession, and everything the job teaches about protecting people's data shaped how Lanyard is built. The best way to protect your data is to never collect it in the first place.</p>

      <h2>Say hello</h2>
      <p>Writing about Lanyard? The <a href="/press">press kit</a> has the facts, the story angles, and the assets. For everything else, email <a href="mailto:dan@lanyardpass.com">dan@lanyardpass.com</a>. It's one person on the other end, and he reads every message.</p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
  .legal { background: var(--off-white); color: var(--ink); }
  .legal__inner {
    max-width: 44rem;
    margin-inline: auto;
    padding: clamp(3rem, 8vw, 5.5rem) var(--gutter) clamp(4rem, 10vw, 7rem);
  }
  .legal__label { color: var(--green-primary); margin-bottom: 1rem; }
  .legal__title { font-size: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 2.8rem); line-height: 1.05; }
  .legal__lead {
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin-top: 1.4rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }
  .about__photo { margin: 2rem 0 0.5rem; }
  .about__photo img {
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    box-shadow: var(--shadow-card);
    display: block;
  }
  .about__photo figcaption {
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    margin-top: 0.6rem;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .legal h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-weight: 800;
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    color: var(--ink);
    margin-top: 2.6rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.6rem;
  }
  .legal p {
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.75;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }
  .legal a { color: var(--green-primary); font-weight: 600; }
</style>
